$DATUM Phenol nonaflate 46: To a solution of phenol (4) (536 mg, 5.7 mmol), in
CH2Cl2 (15 mL) cooled to 0 degC was added triethylamine (1.20 mL, 8.55
mmol), followed by nonafluorobutane sulfonyl fluoride (1.54 mL, 8.55
mmol). After complete addition, the mixture was left to warm to rt over
20 hr. Water (10 mL) was added and the mixture was extracted with CH2Cl2
(3 x 2.5 mL) and the organic layers dried (MgSO4), filtered and
concentrated in vacuo. The residue was purified by FC (EtOAc/hexane 1:19)
to yield phenol nonaflate 46 as a colourless oil (2.06 g, 97 %). Rf =
0.44 (EtOAc/petrol 1:9).

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General Procedure for Esterification Using
2GOACC50. To a stirring solution of acid (0.1 mmol), alcohol [or phenol
or thiol (0.1 mmol)], and DMAP (1.2 mg, 10 mmol %) in CH2Cl2 (0.5 mL) at
0 °C was added dropwise a solution of 2GOACC50 (47 mg, 0.15 mmol) in
CH2Cl2 (0.5 mL). After complete addition, the ice bath was removed, and
the reaction solution was stirred at rt for 2 h. The reaction mixture was
precipitated by addition to Et2O followed by filtration. The resulting
ether solution was washed with water to eliminate DMAP, concentrated
under reduced pressure, and filtered through silica gel (EtOAc). the
corresponding ester in good to excellent yield and purity. Product 6j 1H
NMR (400 MHz, CDCl3), δ, J (Hz): 7.39 (dt, J = 8.0, 2.2, 2H), 7.27- 7.22
(m, 1H), 7.11-7.08 (m, 2H), 3.45 (t, J = 6.7, 2H), 2.60 (t, J = 7.4, 2H),
1.94 (qn, J = 7.1, 2H), 1.81 (qn, J = 7.6, 2H), 1.64-1.56 (m, 2H) 13C NMR
(100 MHz, CDCl3), δ: 171.9, 150.6, 129.4, 125.8, 121.5, 34.1, 33.5, 32.3,
27.6, 24.0 MS (HP 6890 GC/MS, EI) m/z (%): 272 ([M+2]+., 15), 270 (M+.,
15), 179 (37), 177 (37), 94 (100), 69 (44), 65 (10), 55 (13)

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: Representative procedure for O-arylation
reaction of phenols with aryl halides Cu-catalyst (0.05 g) in DMSO (5 mL)
was taken in a 100- mL R.B flask and stirred at room temperature for 10
min. Then aryl halide (1 mmol), phenol (1 mmol), tetrabutylammonium
bromide (tBu4NBr) (0.1 mmol), K2CO3 (1 mmol), dihexyl ether (5 mL) and
DMSO (5 mL) were added. The final reaction mixture was refluxed for 12 h
at 130 °C under an open air condition. The products were collected at
different time intervals and identified by GCMS and quantified by GC
using dihexyl ether as internal standard. After cooling to room
temperature, the reaction was extracted with ethyl acetate (3 x 20 mL),
and the combined organic layers were dried with anhydrous Na2SO4 by
vacuum. The filtrate was concentrated by vacuum and the resulting residue
was purified by column chromatography on silica gel to provide the
desired product. The product was purified by column chromatography, and
its identity confirmed by comparison of color and NMR spectra with those
reported in the literature or authentic samples from our laboratories.
2-Methoxy-diphenylether (4j). Colorless liquid [55]. 1H NMR (CDCl3, 400
MHz) δ : 3.77 (s, 3H), 6.81-6.90 (m, 3H), 6.91-6.94 (m, 1H), 6.96-7.02
(m, 2H), 7.03-7.10 (m, 1H), 7.16-7.25 (m, 2H); 13C NMR (CDCl3, 100 MHz) δ
: 56, 112.9, 117.3, 121.1, 121.2, 122.6, 124.9, 129.6, 145.1, 151.6, 158.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES
$DATUM solid-supported catalyst, catalyst recyclable, Ullmann reaction,
chloromethylated polystyrene anchored imidazole-copper prepared and used
as catalyst, alternative preparation shown
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):TITLE
$DATUM Open air O-arylation reaction of phenols with aryl halides catalyzed by
polymer-anchored copper(II) complexes
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):AUTHOR
$DATUM Islam, Manirul; Mondal, Sanchita; Mondal, Paramita; Roy, Anupam Singha;
Hossain, Dildar; Mobarak, Manir

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: Diaryl Ethers 2; General Procedure. The
appropriate diaryliodonium tosylate 1 (0.6 mmol) was added to a soln of
the phenol (0.5 mmol) and K2CO3 (140 mg, 1.0 mmol) in MeCN (3 mL) at 50
°C and the obtained mixture was stirred for 6 h at 50 °C. The mixture was
quenched with H2O (10 mL) and then extracted with CHCl3 (3 × 25 mL). The
combined organic layers were dried (Na2SO4) and concentrated in vacuo.
The residue was purified by short column chromatography (silica gel) to
give the diaryl ether. 4-Chlorophenyl Phenyl Ether (2k). Colorless oil;
yield: 99.2 mg (97%). [Ar2I]+-OTs: 1d. Time:5 h. IR (neat): 1012, 1242,
1506, 1585 cm-1. 1H NMR (500 MHz, CDCl3): δ = 7.34 (dd, J = 8.6, 7.5 Hz,
2 H), 7.28 (d, J = 8.9 Hz, 2 H), 7.12 (t, J = 7.5 Hz, 1 H), 7.00 (d, J =
8.6 Hz, 2 H), 6.94 (d, J = 8.9 Hz, 2 H). 13C NMR (125 MHz, CDCl3): δ =
156.9, 155.9, 129.9, 129.7, 128.2, 123.6, 120.0, 118.9. HRMS: m/z [M]+
calcd for C12H9O35Cl: 204.0336; found: 204.0335.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES
$DATUM regioselective, alternative preparation shown
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):TITLE
$DATUM Facile preparation of unsymmetrical diaryl ethers from unsymmetrical
diaryliodonium tosylates and phenols with high regioselectivity
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):AUTHOR
$DATUM Kakinuma, Yohji; Moriyama, Katsuhiko; Togo, Hideo

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM Preparation 32: 5-Fluoro-2-phenoxybenzonitrile. Potassium carbonate
(2.90g, 21mmol) was added to a solution of phenol (791mg, 8.4mmol) in 30
ml of N,N-dimethylformamide. The reaction mixture was stirred for 15
minutes at room temperature. and then 2,5-difluorobenzonitrile (973mg,
7mmol) was added. The resulting mixture was heated to 100°C for 18 hours,
after which time it was allowed to cool to room temperature. It was then
concentrated in vacuo. The resulting residue was diluted with ethyl
acetate (50ml), and then washed with water (2×100ml) and 1M sodium
hydroxide solution (100ml). The organic layer was dried over sodium
sulfate, filtered and evaporated under reduced pressure to afford the
title compound, as a yellow oil, 1.449g, 97%. 1HNMR(400MHz, CDCl3) δ:
6.87(q, 1H), 7.05(d, 2H), 7.21(m, 2H), 7.33-7.43(m, 3H); LRMS APCI+ m/z
214[MH]+.

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General procedure for preparation of
unsaturated aryloxy acids. A mixture of the phenol 1a-l (20.0 mmol),
2-bromoenoate ester 2a-c (22 mmol), K2CO3 (50 mmol) and MeCN (20 mL) was
stirred at 80 °C for 16 h. The mixture was cooled to 35 °C and water (15
mL) was added. The upper organic phase was washed with 1M KOH (2 mL) and
was then stirred with 45% aq KOH (3 mL) and water (10 mL) for 20 h at 22
°C to give a homogeneous mixture. The mixture was evaporated to half its
volume at 30 °C and was diluted with water (20 mL) at 20 °C. The aqueous
solution was assayed by quantitative HPLC for yield of 3a-m. 5M HCl (8.0
mL) was added to the mixture (pH <2) was stirred at 10-15 °C for 2h. The
mixture was filtered and the filter cake was washed with water (60 mL)
and 3:1 water/MeCN (20 mL). The filter cake was dried.
(2Z)-2-(Phenoxy)oct-2-enoic acid (3l). mp (dicyclohexylamine salt) =
156-158 °C; 1H NMR (free acid, 400 MHz, CDCl3) δ 11.47 (br s, 1 H), 7.30
(m, 2 H), 7.03 (td, J = 7.4, 0.7, 1 H), 6.93 (dd, J = 7.8, 0.7, 2 H),
6.79 (t, J = 7.7, 1 H), 2.24 (q, J = 7.5, 2 H), 1.46 (m, 2 H), 1.30 (m, 4
H), 0.88 (m, 3 H); 13C NMR (free acid, 100 MHz,CDCl3) δ 168.5, 157.3,
140.3, 135.6, 129.6, 122.3, 115.0, 31.5, 27.9, 26.1, 22.4, 13.9; Anal.
Calcd for C26H41NO3 (dicyclohexylamine salt): C, 75.14; H, 9.94. Found:
C, 74.88; H, 10.24.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES

$DATUM 4'-Methoxybenzyloxybenzene (1i).23 To a solution of phenol 2i (600 mg,
6.35 mmol) in anhydrous THF were added tetrabutylammonium iodide (236 mg,
0.64 mmol, 10 mol %), potassium carbonate (2.64 g, 19.1 mmol), and
p-methoxybenzyl chloride (0.9 mL, 6.7 mmol). The reaction mixture was
heated at reflux for 20 h, cooled at room temperature, and quenched with
a saturated aqueous solution of ammonium chloride. The aqueous layer was
extracted with dichloro-methane. The organic layer was washed with brine,
dried over anhydrous sodium sulfate, and evaporated. The crude residue
was purified by flash chromatography to afford 1i. White solid, yield
1.31 g, 97%. 1H NMR (300 MHz, CDCl3) δ 7.35 (d, J = 9.0 Hz, 2 H), 7.26
(t, J = 7.2 Hz, 1 H), 7.03-6.88 (m, 6 H), 5.00 (s, 2 H), 3.82 (s, 3 H);
13C NMR (75 MHz, CDCl3) δ 158.8, 137.1, 129.5, 128.6, 127.9, 127.5,
120.9, 114.8, 69.9.

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General/Typical Procedure: Preparation of
methyl
3-{[(2E)-2-[3-(4-fluorophenyl)isoxazol-5-yl]2-(propoxyimino)ethyl]oxy}benzoate.
18 mg (0.053 mmol) of
(1Z)-2-bromo-1-[3-(4-fluorophenyl)isoxazol-5-yl]ethanon O-propyloxime,
8.0 mg (0.053 mmol) of methyl 3-hydroxy benzoate and 26 mg (0.079 mmol)
of cesium carbonate were stirred in acetonitrile solvent under reflux for
30 minutes, and then solvent was removed to give 15 mg of the title
compound using column chromatography in a yield of 69%. Preparation of
(1E)-1-[3-(4-fluorophenyl)isoxazol-5-yl]-2- phenoxyethanon O-propyloxime.
10 mg of the title compound was obtained in a yield of 97% in the same
manner as in PREPARATION 2, except that 10 mg (0.029 mmol) of
(1Z)-2-bromo-1-[3-(4- fluorophenyl)isoxazol-5-yl]ethanon O-propyloxime
and 2.8 mg (0.029 mmol) of phenol were used. NMR: 1H-NMR(CDCl3) δ
7.85∼7.78(2H, m), 7.36(1H, s), 7.32∼7.27(2H, m), 7.19∼7.14(2H, m),
7.03∼7.93(3H, m), 5.09(2H, s), 4.32(H, t, J=8Hz), 1.86∼1.77(2H, m),
1.01(3H, t, J=8Hz). Mass(EI) 355(M ++1).

$DATUM Step 3: Preparation of 4-bromo-1-chloro-2-(phenoxymethyl)benzene To a
solution of 4-bromo-1-chloro-2-(chloromethyl)benzene (12.2 g, 50.85 mmol)
and phenol (4.79 g, 50.85 mmol) in DMF (102 mL) under nitrogen
atmosphere, K2CO3 was added (35.14 g, 254.25 mmol). The resulting mixture
was stirred at r.t. for 18 h. After completion of the reaction as
confirmed by TLC, the reaction mixture was passed through celite plug and
the filterate was evaporated. The residue obtained was dissolved in ethyl
acetate (100 mL) and washed with water (2 x 100 mL) and brine (2 x 100
mL) successively. The organic layer was dried over Na2SO4 and
concentrated in vacuo to afford crude product which was purified by
column chromatography (silica gel, 1: 9 Ethyl acetate: Pet. Ether) to
afford the title compound. Yield 14.7 g, 97.3%. ESIMS (m/z): 297.6 (M-1).
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES

$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: To a solution of carboxylic acid (1.0 eq.),
phenol (2.0 eq.) and DMAP (1.2 eq.) in CH2Cl2 (1 M) was added DCC (1.5
eq.) at rt. The resulting mixture was refluxed overnight. The
heterogeneous reaction mixture was cooled to rt and filtered through a
short pad of silica gel with suction and the product was eluted with
ether. The filtrate was concentrated in vacuo and the crude residue was
purified either by flash column chromatography or by recrystallization.
(E)-phenyl 3-(2-chlorophenyl)acrylate. Following the general procedure,
the title compound was synthesized from (E)-phenyl
3-(2-chlorophenyl)acrylate (1.10 g, 6.0 mmol, 1.0 eq.), phenol (1.13 g,
12.0 mmol, 2.0 eq.), DMAP (879.6 mg, 7.2 mmol, 1.2 eq.) and DCC (1.86 g,
9 mmol, 1.5 eq.) in CH2Cl2 (6 mL). After flash column chromatography
(eluent: pet. ether/ether 20:10), the product was obtained as a yellowish
oil, which solidified (1.50 g, 97%) under high vacuum. Rf: 0.47 (pet.
ether/ether 3:1); 1H NMR (CDCl3, 400 MHz): δ 8.29 (d, J = 16.0 Hz, 1H),
7.70 (dd, J = 3.2, 2.0 Hz, 1H), 7.46-7.40 (m, 3H), 7.37-7.32 (m, 2H),
7.30-7.24 (m, 1H), 7.20-7.17 (m, 2H), 6.63 (d, J = 16.0 Hz, 1H); 13C NMR
(CDCl3, 100 MHz): δ 164.9, 150.7, 142.2, 135.1, 132.4, 131.4, 130.3,
129.4, 127.8, 127.2, 125.9, 121.6, 119.9; IR (thin film): 1734, 1635,
1592, 1492, 1471, 1442, 1314, 1266, 1238, 1198, 1163, 1143, 1052, 1040,
977, 757, 723, 690 cm-1; Mp: 74 °C; HRMS (TOF ES+): calcd for [M + H+,
C15H12ClO2]+ 259.0520, found 259.0517.

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM 4-Hydroxy-4’-nitroazobenzene (4-1). p-Nitroaniline (5.5 g, 40 mmol) was
dissolved in a mixture of water (20 ml) and 42 wt% tetrafluoroboric acid
(3.0 g, 80 mmol), and the solution was cooled to 0°C. With stirring, an
aqueous solution of sodium nitrite (2.8 g, 40 mmol, water 20 ml) was
added dropwise into the solution to generate diazonium salt. After the
resulting mixture was stirred for 10 min, a 100 ml aqueous solution of
phenol (3.9 g, 40 mmol) and potassium carbonate (5.6 g, 40 mmol) was
slowly added, and then the mixture was stirred for 2 h at 0°C. The pH of
the resulting mixture was adjusted to 3 by the addition of hydrochloric
acid. The precipitate was collected by suction filtration, and extracted
with ethyl acetate. The organic layer was dried with anhydrous magnesium
sulfate. After evaporation of the solvent, the residue was recrystallized
from methanol. 4-1 as orange-yellow solid (9,3 g, 96 %). 1H NMR (300 MHz,
chloroform (CDCl3): δ 5.40 (br, 1H), 6.96 (d, J = 8.1 Hz, 2H), 7.90-7.98
(m, 4H), 8.35 (d, J = 7.8 Hz, 2H).
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):TITLE
$DATUM Formation of Bragg Gratings with Large Angular Multiplicity by Means of
the Photoinduced Reorientation of Azobenzene Copolymers
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):AUTHOR
$DATUM Saishoji, Aya; Sato, Daisuke; Shishido, Atsushi; Ikeda, Tomiki
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):CITATION
$DATUM Langmuir (2007), 23(1), 320-326

$DATUM 3,3-Diarylpropy-1-ynols 2; General Procedure Using a Solvent To a soln of
arylpropargyl alcohol 1 (1 mmol) and nucleophile (1 mmol) in MeCN (5 mL)
was added PMA-silica gel (1 mol%). The mixture was stirred at r.t. for
the appropriate time. When the reaction was complete (TLC), the mixture
was filtered and washed with CH2Cl2. The combined organic filtrates were
evaporated to dryness in vacuo. The crude product was purified by column
chromatography (EtOAc-hexane). 4-(1,3-Diphenylprop-2-ynyl)phenol (2a)
Brownish yellow sticky liquid. Data are in accordance with the
literature.5,9a Yield 96%. 1H NMR (300 MHz, CDCl3): δ = 4.98 (br s, 1 H,
OH), 5.09 (s, 1 H), 6.71 (d, J = 8.3 Hz, 2 H), 7.15-7.32 (m, 9 H), 7.36
(d, J = 7.5 Hz, 2 H), 7.41-7.47 (m, 1 H).

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM 3,3-Diarylpropy-1-ynols 2; General Procedure under Solvent-Free
Conditions To a mixture of arylpropargyl alcohol 1 (1 mmol) and
nucleophile (1 mmol) was added PMA-silica gel (1 mol%). The mixture was
stirred at r.t. for the appropriate time. When the reaction was complete
(TLC), the mixture was diluted with Et2O and filtered. The combined
organic filtrates were evaporated to dryness in vacuo to yield the crude
product, which was purified by column chromatography (EtOAc-hexane). The
silica gel supported PMA was separated and resubjected to this protocol
with the same propargyl alcohol for propargylation to produce the
products with consistent yields 4-(1,3-Diphenylprop-2-ynyl)phenol (2a)
Brownish yellow sticky liquid. Data are in accordance with the
literature.5,9a Yield 96%. 1H NMR (300 MHz, CDCl3): δ = 4.98 (br s, 1 H,
OH), 5.09 (s, 1 H), 6.71 (d, J = 8.3 Hz, 2 H), 7.15-7.32 (m, 9 H), 7.36
(d, J = 7.5 Hz, 2 H), 7.41-7.47 (m, 1 H).
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES
$DATUM green chemistry-catalyst, reaction run with solvent gave identical yield,
Friedel-Crafts alkylation, no solvent, silica gel used
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):TITLE
$DATUM PMA-silica gel catalyzed propargylation of aromatic compounds with
arylpropargyl alcohols under solvent-free conditions
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):AUTHOR

Sekhar; Satyanarayana, Kamani; Yadav, Jhillu Singh

$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: Representative procedure for O-arylation
reaction of phenols with aryl halides Cu-catalyst (0.05 g) in DMSO (5 mL)
was taken in a 100- mL R.B flask and stirred at room temperature for 10
min. Then aryl halide (1 mmol), phenol (1 mmol), tetrabutylammonium
bromide (tBu4NBr) (0.1 mmol), K2CO3 (1 mmol), dihexyl ether (5 mL) and
DMSO (5 mL) were added. The final reaction mixture was refluxed for 12 h
at 130 °C under an open air condition. The products were collected at
different time intervals and identified by GCMS and quantified by GC
using dihexyl ether as internal standard. After cooling to room
temperature, the reaction was extracted with ethyl acetate (3 x 20 mL),
and the combined organic layers were dried with anhydrous Na2SO4 by
vacuum. The filtrate was concentrated by vacuum and the resulting residue
was purified by column chromatography on silica gel to provide the
desired product. The product was purified by column chromatography, and
its identity confirmed by comparison of color and NMR spectra with those
reported in the literature or authentic samples from our laboratories.
4-Phenoxybenzonitrile (4c). Oil [51]. Yield 96%. 1H NMR (CDCl3, 400 MHz)
δ : 7.57 (d, J= 8.6 Hz, 2H), 7.42 (t, J= 7.9 Hz, 2H), 7.25 (t, J= 7.6 Hz,
1H), 7.0 (d, J= 7.9 Hz, 2H), 6.89 (d, J= 8.8 Hz, 2H); 13C NMR (CDCl3, 100
MHz) δ : 160.4, 151.1, 135.8, 131.5, 123.0, 118.4, 116.5, 120.3, 101.5.

$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: Typical Procedure for Nucleophilic Aromatic
Substitution of 2- and 4-Fluoro-1-nitrobenzene by Alkoxides.
2-[(2-Butyl-2-propenyl)oxy]-1-nitrobenzene (1a).- In a 100-mL,
threenecked, round-bottomed flask equipped with an addition funnel, a
magnetic stir bar and a condenser, 0.32 g of 60% NaH in mineral oil (8.0
mmol) was washed with hexane (3x) and suspended in 10 mL of DMF. Stirring
was started and a solution of 0.86 g (7.5 mmol) of 2-butyl- 2-propen-1-ol
in 10 mL of DMF was added dropwise at room temperature. The mixture was
stirred for 1 h at room temperature and 0.71 g (5.0 mmol) of
2-fluoro-1-nitrobenzene in 2 mL of DMF was added dropwise. The reaction
became warm and turned dark brown in color. The reaction was stirred for
1 h at room temperature and for 12 h at 50°C, then added to saturated
NH4Cl and extracted with ether (3x). The combined ether layers were
washed with 1 M HCl and saturated NaCl, dried (MgSO4) and concentrated
under vacuum. The crude product was flash chromatographed on a 60 cm x 2
cm silica gel column using 5% ether in hexane. 4-Phenoxy-1-nitrobenzene
(2g).- Prior to the 1 M HCl wash in the workup for 2g, the combined
ethereal extracts were washed with 0.2 M NaOH (until the aqueous washes
remained colorless) to remove any unreacted phenol. The spectral data
matched those reported previously.13 Mp: 58-59°C. Lit. mp 58-59°C
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES
$DATUM optimization study
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):TITLE
$DATUM A versatile and convenient synthesis of alkyl nitroaromatic ethers by
nucleophilic aromatic substitution
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):AUTHOR
$DATUM Bunce, Richard A.; Easton, Kerry M.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):CITATION
$DATUM Organic Preparations and Procedures International (2004), 36(1), 76-81

$DATUM Synthesis of DCHA. Synthesis of the Amine Hydrochloride 5. Monoacetyl
ethylenediamine (1.08 g, 10.62 mmol) was added to a stirred flask
containing 25.0 g (265.6 mmol) of melted phenol and 0.64 g (7.97 mmol) of
NaOH (50% w/w) at 30-35 °C. Then, 1.57 g (10.62 mmol) of glyoxylic acid
(50% in water) was added slowly dropwise to the solution, keeping the
temperature below 40 °C. The mixture was kept at 70-75 °C for 2 h and
then at room temperature for 20 min. After the addition of water (60 mL),
the reaction was extracted with CH2Cl2 (3 x 20 mL), and the solvent was
evaporated under reduced pressure to yield 1.9 g (96%) of amide 4 as a
solid. 1H NMR (D2O) δ 7.17-7.04 (m, 2H, ArH), 6.82-6.66 (m, 2H, ArH),
4.07 (s, 1H, CH), 3.26-3.16 (m, 2H, CH2), 2.84-2.74 (m, 1H, CH2),
2.71-2.54 (m, 1H, CH2), 1.83 (s, 3H, CH3); 13C NMR (D2O) δ 176.8 (C=O),
174.9 (C=O), 156.6, 130,4, 130.3, 122.8, 120.1, 116.8 (ArC), 64.9 (CH),
45.9 (CH2), 38.3 (CH2), 22.2 (CH3).; IR (KBr) ν 3423 (NH), 1656 (C=O,
amide I), 1578, 1444 (NC=O, amide II), 1377, 1104, 742 cm-1.

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General Procedure for the Preparation of 1,6-Bis(phenoxy)-2,4-hexadiyne
Derivatives. (Prop-2-ynyloxy)benzene derivatives were prepared from the
reaction of the appropriate phenol (1 equiv) with propargyl bromide (1.5
equiv) at room temperature in DMF in the presence of potassium carbonate
(2 equiv). Purification of the crude product was achieved via flash
column chromatography. Then, in a 50 mL flask were dissolved
(prop-2-ynyloxy)benzene derivatives (6 mmol) in 4 mL of DMF. To the
solution were added copper(I) chloride (30 mg, 5 mol %), 0.1 mL (10 mol
%) of N,N,N′,N′-tetramethylethylenediamine, and 0.1 mL (10 mol %) of
pyridine. The mixture was bubbled with oxygen and stirred at room
temperature for 6-12 h. A 30 mL portion of DMF was added, and the mixture
was filtered through a short silica column to remove copper. The filtrate
was poured into 100 mL of water. The resultant precipitate was filtered,
washed with water, and dried under vacuum. A beige powder (36-96%).
1,6-Bis(phenoxy)-2,4-hexadiyne (1a):10 white solid (96%, 980 mg). mp
61-64°C; 1H NMR (400 MHz, CDCl3) δ 7.33-7.28 (m, 4H), 7.02-6.93 (m, 6H),
4.75 (s, 4H); 13C NMR (100 MHz, CDCl3) δ 157.8, 130.0, 122.2, 115.3,
75.0, 71.4, 56.6; IR (pellet) 3062, 3041, 2912, 1598, 1494, 1361, 1211,
1034 cm-1.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):TITLE

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):AUTHOR

$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: To a solution of tertiary alcohol of general
formula II in dichloroethane was added phenol (5 equiv) and p-TSA (7.5
equiv). The reaction mixture was heated to 90 °C for 2-4 h and then
cooled to room temperature. The solid (mainly p-TSA) was filtered off and
washed with dichloroethane or DCM. The solution was concentrated and the
residue was purified by chromatography (1% MeOH in DCM or mixtures of
petroleum ether and EtOAc) to afford racemic compounds of general formula
III. (RS)-6,7-Difluoro-3-(4-hydroxyphenyl)-3-propylindolin-2-one (15).
Preparation of 15 was performed according to general procedure A using
6,7-difluoroindoline-2,3-dione and n-propylmagnesium bromide. Yield 96%.
1H NMR ((CD3)2SO) δ 11.20 (bs, 1H), 9.38 (bs, 1H), 7.04 (m, 4H), 6.69 (m,
2H), 2.13 (m, 2H), 1.21 (m, 2H), 1.02 (m, 2H), 0.83 (m, 3H). HRMS m/z
calcd for C17H15F2NO2 [M+Na], 326.0969; found, 326.0996.

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: Representative Procedure for Diazotization and
Diazocoupling Reactions In a typical experiment, 4.67 g of (0.05 mol) of
aniline was adsorbed on 8 g of clay (KK) catalyst and cooled to 0°C. To
this, 4.34 g (0.1 mol) of NaNO2 in 15 mL H2O was added dropwise for a
period of 1 h. After the addition of NaNO2, 4.67 g (0.05 mol) of phenol
was added to this ice cold diazonium clay complex and was brought to room
temperature with constant stirring and kept at room temperature for 1 h.
The reaction mixture was then repeatedly extracted into alcohol. The
alcohol extracts evaporation under vacuum afforded 1. 5, yield 96%.
IR(KBr cm-1) 3400-3450 (OH), 1621 (-N=N-), 1510, 1340 (NO2), UV (λmax nm)
270, 390. 1H NMR δ 8.1-8.3 (m, 4H, phenyl), 6.7-7.36 (m, 4H,
nitrophenyl), GC-MS OV 101, Rt 11.30 min; m/z 243 (M+).
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES
$DATUM green chemistry-catalyst, Bentonite Clay catalyst used, montmorillonite
K10 clay catalyst and Kaolinite Clay Catalyst KK gave similar results
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):TITLE
$DATUM Modified clays as efficient acid-base catalyst systems for diazotization
and diazocoupling reactions

$DATUM Bahulayan, Damodaran; John, Litka; Lalithambika, Malathy

$DATUM Synthetic Communications (2003), 33(6), 863-869

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General procedure for the methoxymethylation
of alcohols and phenols at room temperature To a solution of alcohol or
phenol (1 mmol) in FDMA (7 mmol), 0.01 g ZrO(OTf)2 (2.5 mol%) was added
and the mixture was stirred at room temperature for the appropriate time
according to Table 2. The progress of the reaction was monitored by TLC
(eluent cyclohexane/ethyl acetate, 4:1). After completion of the
reaction, the excess FDMA was evaporated and 10 cm3 Et2O was added and
the catalyst was filtered. The filtrate was evaporated and the crude
product was purified by column chromatography on silica gel (eluent
cyclohexane/ethyl acetate, 4:1) to afford the pure product. 3p, yield
96%.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES

chemistry-solvent (free), no solvent
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):TITLE

catalyzed by reusable ZrO(OTf)2 under solvent-free conditions

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM 3-(Benzyloxy)-5-[(1S,2S)-2-(phenoxymethyl)cyclopropyl]pyridine
1,1'-(Azodicarbonyl)dipiperidine (316 mg, 1.25 mmol, 1.6 equiv.) was
dissolved in 2 mL of toluene (dried with molecular sieve 3Å ) in a 10 mL
round-bottom flask with a side neck. The flask was equipped with rubber
septa and a magnetic stirrer. The atmosphere was exchanged with Ar (3
times), and the flask was cooled with an ice bath. Tributylphosphine (309
μL, 1.25 mmol, 1.6 equiv.) was added dropwise. The mixture was warmed to
room temperature and stirred for 10 min. The colorless solution formed
was then added dropwise (via syringe) to a solution of
(1S,2S)-2-(5-benzyloxy-3-pyridyl)cyclopropylmethanol (200 mg, 0.78 mmol,
1 equiv.) and phenol (118 mg, 1.25 mmol, 1.6 equiv.) in a 25 mL
round-bottom flask (equipped with a magnetic stirrer and an Ar balloon,
and cooled with an ice bath). The resulting mixture was warmed to room
temperature and stirred overnight. The reaction was quenched by addition
of saturated NaHCO3 solution (10 mL), and the mixture was extracted with
EtOAc (3 x 20 mL). The combined organic phases were concentrated, and the
residue was purified by CC on SiO2 (25 x 2.5 cm, EtOAc/hexanes 2:1) to
give the crude phenyl ether as a white solid (248 mg, 96%), which was
used for next step without further purification.
3-(Benzyloxy)-5-[(1S,2S)-2-(phenoxymethyl)cyclopropyl]pyridine, yield
(248 mg, 96%) MS (EI) m/z 331 (M+, 0.2%).

$DATUM 2.3.7. Synthesis of Phenoxytrispentadecylphenoxyboronsubphthalocyanine
(PhO-(PDPhO)3BsubPc,6b) . Cl-(PDPhO)3BsubPc (6a, 4.0 g, 3 mmol) and
phenol (1.41 g, 15 mmol) were mixed together in 35mL of toluene in a
round bottomed flask under a steady stream of inert Argon gas, and
refluxed for 17 h. After cooling, the toluenewas removed by rotary
evaporation, and the pure product was obtained by Kaufmann column
chromatography on alumina with DCM as the eluent. Removal of the DCM by
rotary evaporation. A purple waxy solid. Yield: 4.03 g (96%). 1H NMR
400MHz (CDCl3) 8.69-8.78 (mr, 3H), 8.24-8.31 (mr, 3H), 7.50-7.62 (mr,
3H), 7.29-7.37 (mr, 3H), 7.06 (t, 3H), 6.76 (t, 2H), 6.61 (t, 1H), 5.38
(d, 2H), 2.57-2.68 (mr, 6H), 1.64 (s, 7H), 1.23 (m, 74H), 0.87 (t, 9H);
UV-vis (CHCl3) λ max = 570 nm; GPC R T (min) = 6.80 (>99.9%).

Using a Solvent To a soln of arylpropargyl alcohol 1 (1 mmol) and
nucleophile (1 mmol) in MeCN (5 mL) was added PMA-silica gel (1 mol%).
The mixture was stirred at r.t. for the appropriate time. When the

$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: 3,3-Diarylpropy-1-ynols 2; General Procedure
under Solvent-Free Conditions To a mixture of arylpropargyl alcohol 1 (1
mmol) and nucleophile (1 mmol) was added PMA-silica gel (1 mol%). The
mixture was stirred at r.t. for the appropriate time. When the reaction
was complete (TLC), the mixture was diluted with Et2O and filtered. The
combined organic filtrates were evaporated to dryness in vacuo to yield
the crude product, which was purified by column chromatography
(EtOAc-hexane). The silica gel supported PMA was separated and
resubjected to this protocol with the same propargyl alcohol for
propargylation to produce the products with consistent yields

liquid, yield 96%. IR (KBr): 3379, 2924, 2386, 2169, 1600, 1506, 1443,

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General Procedure for the NHC-Catalyzed
Oxidation of Aldehydes RCHO to the Corresponding Esters RCO2R' (GP 1):
DBU (3 mol% or 1.1 equiv) was added to a solution of
1,3-dimethyltriazolium iodide (2 mol%) and alcohol R’OH (0.5 mL) in THF
(2.0 mL) under argon atmosphere. The mixture was stirred for 5 minutes,
followed by the addition of aldehyde RCHO (1.0 equiv) and
3,3',5,5'-tetra-tert-butyldiphenoquinone (1.0 equiv). The reaction
mixture was stirred at room temperature for 2-6 hours until consumption
of starting aldehyde as checked by TLC. The solvent was removed under
vacuum and the residue was purified by flash silica gel column
chromatography by using a mixture of pentane and diethyl ether as eluent.
(E)-Cinnamic acid phenyl ester: According to GP 1 with (E)-cinnamaldehyde
(66 mg, 0.5 mmol), DBU (83 mg, 0.55 mmol), 1,3-dimethyltriazolium iodide
(2.3 mg, 10 µmol), 3,3',5,5' tetra-tert-butyldiphenoquinone (205 mg, 0.5
mmol) and phenol (71 mg, 0.75 mmol) in THF (5.0 mL) for 2 h and
SiO2-chromatography (pentane:Et2O, 60:1) to afford the corresponding
ester (107 mg, 96%, contains 2% of phenyl 3-phenylpropionate).
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES
$DATUM chemoselective
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):TITLE
$DATUM NHC Catalyzed Oxidations of Aldehydes to Esters: Chemoselective Acylation
of Alcohols in Presence of Amines
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):AUTHOR
$DATUM De Sarkar, Suman; Grimme, Stefan; Studer, Armido
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):CITATION
$DATUM Journal of the American Chemical Society (2010), 132(4), 1190-1191

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: 3,3-Diarylpropy-1-ynols 2; General Procedure
Using a Solvent To a soln of arylpropargyl alcohol 1 (1 mmol) and
nucleophile (1 mmol) in MeCN (5 mL) was added PMA-silica gel (1 mol%).
The mixture was stirred at r.t. for the appropriate time. When the
reaction was complete (TLC), the mixture was filtered and washed with
CH2Cl2. The combined organic filtrates were evaporated to dryness in
vacuo. The crude product was purified by column chromatography
(EtOAc-hexane).
4-[1-(4-Methoxyphenyl)-3-(trimethylsilyl)prop-2-ynyl]phenol (2f) Pale
yellow sticky liquid, yield 96%. IR (neat): 3415, 2957, 2927, 2855, 2376,
2169, 1608, 1508, 1459, 1248, 1174, 1034, 842, 761, 573 cm-1. 1H NMR (300
MHz, CDCl3): δ = 0.12 (s, 9 H), 3.69 (s, 3 H), 4.66 (br s, 1 H, OH), 4.77
(s, 1 H), 6.62 (d, J = 8.3 Hz, 2 H), 6.71 (d, J = 9.0 Hz, 2 H), 7.07 (d,
J = 8.3 Hz, 2 H),7.12 (d, J = 8.3 Hz, 2 H). 13C NMR (75 MHz, CDCl3): δ =
1.0, 42.4, 55.2, 88.6, 107.2, 113.9, 115.3, 128.7, 128.9, 134.0, 134.2,
154.3, 158.4. MS (ESI): m/z = 311 [M+ + H]. HRMS: m/z [M + H]+ calcd for
C19H23O2Si: 311.1475; found: 311.1467.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General procedure: In a typical experiment,
0.5 mmol of NaH was placed in a flame-dried, round-bottomed flask
equipped with a stirring bar and septum. Then 2 mL of anhydrous Et2O was
transferred into the reaction flask, and the suspension obtained was
cooled to 0 °C. After that, 0.5 mmol of the starting alcohol was added to
the reaction mixture, which was then stirred for 30 min at the same
temperature and then for 2 h at room temperature. After salt formation
was complete, the reaction mixture was cooled to -20 °C and 0.5 mmol of
acyl chloride 6 was added drop wise. The reaction mixture was then
stirred for 1 h at the same temperature, allowed to warm to room
temperature and left to stir overnight. The reaction mixture was then
transferred into a separatory funnel and washed sequentially with 10%
HCl, water, 10% water solution of NaHCO3, and water. The organic layer
was separated, and the water layers were carefully extracted with diethyl
ether. All organic fractions were combined and dried over MgSO4. Removal
of the solvent by distillation gave the crude product, which was purified
by column chromatography from pentane. SF5CF2-Containing Ester 8e, Yield:
96% (NMR yield).
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):TITLE

Block

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM Procedure for Intermediate 4. A stirred mixture of ethyl
3-phenylpropiolate (1 mmol), phenol 1a (1.1 mmol), anhydrous potassium
carbonate (2 mmol), and dimethylformamide (DMF, 2 mL) was heated to 60 °C
for 2 h. The temperature of reaction was cooled to room temperature. The
resulting reaction solution was quenched with 20 mL of aqueous Na2CO3
(5%). The mixture was transferred to a separating funnel and extracted
with 50 mL of ethyl acetate (EtOAc) four times. The extract was washed
with 50 mL of aqueous sodium hydroxide (NaOH) solution (1%) and again
with 50 mL of water. The organic phase was dried over MgSO4, filtered,
and concentrated in vacuo to afford 96% yield of intermediate 4.
(E/Z)-Ethyl 3-phenoxy-3-phenylacrylate (4). The ratio of two
stereoisomers is 2:1. 1H NMR (ppm) δ 7.62-7.60(m, 6H), 7.45-7.33(m, 11H),
7.25-7.21(m, 5H), 7.16-7.13(m, 2H), 6.99-6.97(m, 6H), 6.16(s, 2H),
5.18(s, 1H), 4.14(q, J = 7.2Hz, 4H), 4.02(q, J = 7.2Hz, 2H), 1.19(t, J =
7.2Hz, 6H), 1.12(t, J = 7.2Hz, 3H); 13C NMR (ppm) δ 170.2, 166.5, 164.4,
161.6, 157.0, 153.9, 134.0, 133.8, 130.5, 130.1, 130.0, 129.4, 129.2,
128.7, 127.7, 127.0, 125.5, 122.2, 121.3, 116.2, 106.4, 98.2, 60.1, 59.8,
14.1, 14.0; HRMS(ESI) calcd for C17H17O3(M++H): 269.1172; found: 269.1167
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General Procedure for the Preparation of 3a-3g A mixture of
5-bromoacenaphthenequinone (2) (260 mg, 1 mmol), corresponding phenol (1
mmol) and K2CO3 (150 mg, 1.1 mmol) was stirred in DMF (20 mL) for 4 h at
60°C. The solution was poured into a saturated NaCl aqueous solution (20
mL), followed by extraction with ethyl acetate (3×20 mL). The organic
layer was collected and dried with MgSO4. After evaporation under reduced
pressure, the product was purified by column chromatography on silica gel
using dichloromethane/petroleum ether (2:1). 5-phenoxyacenaphthenequinone
(3a). Yield: 265 mg, 96%. 1H NMR (400 MHz, CDCl3):δ 8.44 (d, J=8.4 Hz,
1H), 8.35 (d, J=9.2 Hz, 2H), 8.258 (d, J=8.0 Hz, 1H), 8.11 (d, J=8.0 Hz,
1H), 7.69 (t, J=8.0 Hz, 1H), 7.55 (t, J=9.2 Hz, 1H), 7.30 (t, J=9.2 Hz,
2H), 7.16 (d, J=8.4 Hz, 1H). TOF MS (EI+): C18H10O3, calcd for 274.0630,
found 274.0635.

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General Procedure D for Liquid Benzyl
Carbonates. In a nitrogen-filled drybox, Pd(η3-C3H5)Cp (2.1 mg, 10 μmol),
DPEphos (5.9 mg, 11 μmol), and a phenol 4 (1.2 mmol) were put into a 5 ml
screw-capped vial equipped with a stirring bar. After the mixture was
diluted with toluene (1.0 mL), the vial was sealed with a screw cap
containing a PTFE/silicone septum and removed from the drybox. After the
solution was stirred at room temperature for 5 min, a benzyl carbonate 1
(1.0 mmol) was added into the vial through the septum by a syringe. The
reaction mixture was stirred at 60 °C until 1 disappeared (monitored by
GC) and evaporated under reduced pressure. The residue was purified with
a flash column chromatography (EtOAc/hexane). Phenyl
4-(Trifluoromethyl)benzyl Ether (3l) The general procedure D was followed
with use of methyl 4-(trifluoromethyl)benzyl carbonate (1c) (228 mg, 1.0
mmol) and 4a (113 mg, 1.2 mmol). The reaction was conducted for 3 h. The
crude product was purified with a flash column chromatography
(EtOAc/hexane = 1/20) to give 3l (244 mg, 96%) as a colorless solid,
Yield (244 mg, 96%). H NMR (400 MHz, CDCl3, TMS) δ 5.11 (s, 2H),
6.94-7.01 (m, 3H), 7.30 (t, J = 8.0 Hz, 2H), 7.54 (d, J = 8.1 Hz, 2H),
7.63 (d, J = 8.1 Hz, 2H); 13C {1H} NMR (100 MHz, CDCl3) δ 69.0, 114.8,
120.0, 124.1 (q, J = 272 Hz), 125.4 (q, J = 4 Hz), 127.3, 129.6, 130.1
(q, J = 32 Hz), 141.2, 158.4.

$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General Procedure for Preparation of
iNoc-Protected Compounds. To prepare 3a and 3b, phenol 1a (1.20 mmol,
0.113 g) or 4-methoxyphenol 1b (0.95 mmol, 0.235 g) as the starting
material was dissolved in 2 mL of DMF and stirred for 3.5-16 h at 50 °C
in the presence of iNoc reagent 2 (1.2 equiv) and K2CO3 (1.0 equiv).
Phenylpyridin-4-ylmethyl Carbonate 3a. The reaction was performed in 2.5
mL of DMF for 3.5 h. The colorless solid of 3a was obtained by
purification of the crude product by using column chromatography
(Et2O/EtOAc 3:2). Isolated yield: 0.263 g (96%). mp: 53.1-53.5 °C; Rf =
0.48 (silica gel, Et2O/EtOAc 3:2); 1H NMR (400 MHz, CDCl3): δ = 8.58-8.57
(m, 2H), 7.34-7.30 (m, 2H), 7.26-7.11 (m, 5H), 5.20 (s, 2H) ppm; 13C NMR
(100 MHz, CDCl3): δ = 153.7, 151.2, 150.5, 143.9, 129.8, 126.6, 122.2,
121.2, 68.3 ppm; HRMS (ESI+): m/z: [M+H]+ calcd for C13H12NO3+, 230.0812;
found, 230.0808.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):TITLE

$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: Typical Procedure A: Coupling of Aryl Iodides
with Phenols: A sealed tube equipped with a Teflon valve was charged with
a magnetic stir bar, CuBr (7 mg, 0.05mmol, 5 mol %), Cs2CO3 (650 mg, 2
mmol) and any remaining solids (phenols and/or aryl halides). The tube
was evacuated and backfilled with argon (this procedure was repeated
three times). Under a counter flow of argon, 1.2 mmol phenols (if
liquid), 1 mmol aryl halide (if liquid), DMSO (1.5 mL) and ligand L1 (14
mg, 0.10 mmol, 10 mol %) were added by syringe. The tube was evacuated
and backfilled with argon again (this procedure was repeated three times)
and sealed. The reaction mixture was heated to the indicated temperature
(80℃) for the required time period. After cooling to room temperature,
the mixture was diluted with ethyl acetate (10 ml), passed through a
fritted glass filter to remove the inorganic salts and the solvent was
removed under vacuum. The residue was purified by column chromatography
on silica gel and the product was dried under high vacuum for at least 1
h. 1-fluoro-2-phenoxybenzeneProcedure A was followed. Colorless oil: 1H
NMR (400 MHz, CDCl3) δ 7.27-7.39 (2 H, m), 7.15-7.21 (1 H, m), 7.05-7.13
(4 H, m), 6.99 (2 H, d, J =8.0 Hz); 13C NMR (100 MHz, CDCl3) δ 157.4,
155.6, 153.1, 143.8, 143.7, 129.7, 124.8, 124.7, 124.7, 124.7, 123.1,
121.9, 117.3, 117.2, 117.0 (CDCl3 δ 77.1). GC/MS: rt = 6.06 min, M/Z =
188

$DATUM 584-08-7
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):SOL(1):CAS_RN
$DATUM 67-68-5
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):SOL(2):CAS_RN
$DATUM 108-88-3
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM Synthesis of 2-trifluoromethyldiphenyl ether (M1). A 25 mL two-necked
flask was equipped with a Dean-Stark trap connected to a water-cooled
condenser. 2- Nitrobenzotrifluoride (0.6448 g, 3.374 mmol), phenol
(0.3175 g, 3.374 mmol), K2CO3 (0.6995 g, 5.061 mmol), 3.5 mL of DMSO, and
2.0 mL of toluene were added to the flask. The reaction mixture was
heated to 135°C for 4 h at which the toluene was brought to reflux. The
toluene was periodically removed from the Dean-Stark trap, and fresh dry
toluene was added to the reaction mixture to ensure dehydration of the
system. Then, the reaction mixture was stirred at 150°C for 12 h. After
the reaction was complete, the reaction mixture was poured into 50 mL of
distilled water. The product was extracted with dichloromethane (20
mL×3), and washed with 2% NaOH solution (50 mL×1) and distilled water (50
mL×2). After excess solvent was evaporated, the resulting pale yellow
liquid was dried in vacuo at room temperature (0.7702 g, 95.8% yield).
FTIR (NaCl, cm-1): 3043 (aromatic C-H); 1586, 1488 (aromatic C=C); 1246
(C-O-C); 1170-1110 (C-F). 1H NMR (DMSO-d 6, 400.13 MHz, ppm): 7.75 (d,
1H, J = 7.79 Hz); 7.61 (t, 1H, J = 7.84 Hz); 7.41 (t, 2H, J = 7.81 Hz);
7.29 (t, 1H, J = 7.63 Hz); 7.18 (t, 1H, J = 7.69 Hz); 7.03 (d, 2H, J =
8.51 Hz); 6.99 (d, 1H, J = 8.24 Hz). 13C NMR (DMSO-d 6, 100.62 MHz, ppm):
155.94, 154.58, 134.36, 130.18, 127.10 (q, J = 5.1 Hz), 124.23, 123.43
(q, J = 270.7 Hz), 123.41, 119.80 (q, J = 30.5 Hz), 119.35, 118.88. EI
HRMS (m/e): calc. for C13H9F3O, 238.0605; found, 238.0605.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES
$DATUM Dean-Stark trap used
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):TITLE
$DATUM Synthesis of Hyperbranched Poly(arylene ether) from Monomer Containing
Nitro Group: Kinetically Controlled Growth of Polymer Chain through
Dynamic Exchange of End Functional Groups
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):AUTHOR
$DATUM Kim, Yun Jun; Kakimoto, Masa-aki; Kim, Sang Youl
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):CITATION
$DATUM Macromolecules (2006), 39(21), 7190-7192

$RFMT $RIREG SCHEME371 STEP1

$DATUM Phenyl methoxyacetatePhenol (13.0 g, 138 mmol) was dissolved with
stirring under argon in dry Et2O (150 cm3) before the addition of Et3N
(19.0 cm3, 138 mmol). Methoxyacetyl chloride (12.6 cm3, 138 mmol) was
added dropwise over 1 h (exotherms) resulting in the formation of a white
precipitate. The reaction was stirred at room temperature for a further 3
h before being partitioned between Et2O (150 cm3) and water (150 cm3),
the phases were separated and the organic layer washed with brine (150
cm3). Drying (MgSO4) and solvent removal produced product as a pale
yellow oil. Phenyl methoxyacetate, yield 96%. νmax(film)/cm-1 3068, 2935,
2832, 1778, 1593, 1493 and 1197; δH (400 MHz, CDCl3) 3.54(3H, s, OMe),
4.29 (2H, s, CH2), 7.13 (2H, dd, J 8.4 & 0.9, Ar-H), 7.23-7.27 (1H, m,
Ar-H)and 7.39 (2H, t, J 8.4, Ar-H); δC (100 MHz, CDCl3) 59.6 (OMe), 69.2
(CH2), 121.4 (2C, Ar),126.1 (Ar), 129.5 (2C, Ar), 150.2 (Ar) and 168.8
(CO2Ph); m/z (ES+) 166, 138, 108, 77, 65 and 45 (100); (CI+ found: MNH4+
184.0968, C9H14O3N+ requires 184.0968).
